    <main>
        <section id="semantics">
            <h2>Semantics</h2>
            <p>HTML5 introduces new semantic elements that provide a clearer structure to web documents. These elements include <code>&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;section&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>, and more.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="multimedia">
            <h2>Multimedia Support</h2>
            <p>HTML5 brings native support for audio and video playback without the need for third-party plugins. The <code>&lt;audio&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;video&gt;</code> elements allow developers to embed media directly into web pages.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="offline">
            <h2>Offline Web Applications</h2>
            <p>HTML5 introduces features like the Application Cache (<code>AppCache</code>) and Web Storage (<code>localStorage</code> and <code>sessionStorage</code>) to enable web applications to work offline or with reduced connectivity. This is achieved by caching resources locally on the user's device.</p>
        </section>
    </main>

